5.2. Reducing the Resulting Flag Set Based on Performance
Though after the normalization the resulting Ô¨Çag set contains only those Ô¨Çags that aÔ¨Äect the compiled binary,
many of them do not signiÔ¨Åcantly aÔ¨Äect the application‚Äôs performance. To identify Ô¨Çags that aÔ¨Äect performance
the most, we do further performance-based reducing of the resulting conÔ¨Ågurations.
The procedure starts with the original normalized Ô¨Çag set, and then on each step it tries to drop a single Ô¨Çag,
so that its exclusion improves5 the performance. If such Ô¨Çag can not be found, then the Ô¨Çag with the least negative
impact is excluded. This procedure repeats until only the base Ô¨Çags are left (usually -O2).
For the Ô¨Çag set consisting of N Ô¨Çags it requires N ‚àí 1 steps, and on each step the tool performs as many runs
as there are currently Ô¨Çags left in the set, looking for the least signiÔ¨Åcant. So the total number of runs required
by a straightforward implementation of the reducing algorithm does not exceed (N ‚àí 1)(N ‚àí 2)/2, and usually is
less, since we continue traversing the Ô¨Çag set from the Ô¨Çag dropped on the last step if the impact of such operation
was positive. Also, to speedup the process, we‚Äôre Ô¨Årst trying to remove Ô¨Çags in large groups, which are formed
based on the performance impact the Ô¨Çag has shown when reducing the previous conÔ¨Åguration. This way, Ô¨Çags
with historically least negative eÔ¨Äect (for this tuning session) have priority. If removing the whole group decreases
performance, then we again consider the worse half of the group. We continue the dichotomy until a better set is
found or only one option is left.
After that, we proceed with a straightforward algorithm described above. Such a method helps to suÔ¨Éciently
reduce number of runs. Fig 4 shows how the number of runs required to reduce conÔ¨Ågurations of comparable
size changes when sequentially reducing Ô¨Åve best conÔ¨Ågurations. For C-Ray, the minimum number of iterations
required to reduce all Ô¨Åve conÔ¨Ågurations without reusing of previous knowledge or grouping would be 2671, but
in our experiments it was 773. For libevas, the Ô¨Årst conÔ¨Åguration was lucky to drop most of its options at the
Ô¨Årst reducing step, so we didn‚Äôt get many recommendations recorded for the second conÔ¨Åguration. However, both
graphs show a tendency of decreasing number of runs for the subsequent conÔ¨Ågurations.
Fig 5 shows how much the resulting compiler Ô¨Çag set can be reduced for chosen applications. Out of the
original 200 compilation Ô¨Çags, after initial Ô¨Çag normalization by binary hash only 33-62 signiÔ¨Åcant options were
left. Then, the resulting set is further reduced to 12-27 Ô¨Çags by the method described in this section (Ô¨Årst bar).
Out of those, 4-14 options provide 80% of achieved improvement (second bar), so after manual inspection some
of those may be included in the application‚Äôs MakeÔ¨Åle. And 4-17 options in results were actually optimizations
turned oÔ¨Ä from the conÔ¨Åguration speciÔ¨Åed by the -O2 optimization level, or parameters that diÔ¨Äer from their
default values (third bar). Flags in the latter category are the most interesting for compiler developer, because
they may point at potential problems in the compiler default optimizations or to their suboptimal tuning for the
application or the target architecture.

